&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;In a typical data science project we try several models like (logistic regression, SVM, tree-classifiers etc) on our data.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Then we measure the predicting performance of these models to find the best performing one.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Finally we decide to implement the best performing model.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;In this notebook we talk about one of the classification model evaluation tools: Confusion matrix.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;They can help us to see deeper how much reliable our models are.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;We are going to look at the confusion matrices of a variety of Scikit-Learn models and compare them using visual diagnostic tools from Yellowbrick in order to select the best model for our data.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

